{"id":"1811.02037","submitter":"\\'Ad\\'am Gali","authors":"P\\'eter Udvarhelyi, Roland Nagy, Florian Kaiser, Sang-Yun Lee, J\\\"org\n  Wrachtrup, and Adam Gali","title":"Spectrally stable defect qubits with no inversion symmetry for robust\n  spin-to-photon interface","comments":"6 pages, 5 figures, 2 tables","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Applied 11, 044022 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevApplied.11.044022","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Scalable spin-to-photon interfaces require quantum emitters with strong\noptical transition dipole moment and low coupling to phonons and stray electric\nfields. It is known that particularly for coupling to stray electric fields,\nthese conditions can be simultaneously satisfied for emitters that show\ninversion symmetry. Here, we show that inversion symmetry is not a prerequisite\ncriterion for a spectrally stable quantum emitter. We find that identical\nelectron density in ground and excited states can eliminate the coupling to the\nstray electric fields. Further, a strong optical transition dipole moment is\nachieved in systems with altering sign of the ground and excited wavefunctions.\nWe use density functional perturbation theory to investigate an optical center\nthat lacks of inversion symmetry. Our results show that this system close to\nideally satisfies the criteria for an ideal quantum emitter. Our study opens a\nnovel rationale in seeking promising materials and point defects towards the\nrealisation of robust spin-to-photon interfaces.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Nov 2018 21:19:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Nov 2018 10:39:23 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 24 Nov 2018 12:56:05 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 26 Jan 2019 19:55:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-17"}
